  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "Black holes do indeed exist because of their extreme gravitational pull, which arises from the warping of spacetime caused by a concentrated mass. While it is true that light does not have mass, it is important to understand that gravity affects everything with energy, not just objects that have mass.\n\nEinstein's General Theory of Relativity describes gravity not as a force in the traditional sense, but as a curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy. This means that any object with energy, including light (which has energy associated with its frequency), follows the curvature of spacetime. When light passes near a massive object or a black hole, it can be bent and can even be trapped if it crosses the event horizon (the boundary around a black hole beyond which nothing can escape).\n\nIn summary, black holes exist not just because they pull in mass, but because they have a gravitational influence on all forms of energy, including light. That's why black holes can 'swallow' light and why we can't see anything that crosses their event horizons.",
